# Credit derivative  

In finance, a credit derivative is a securitized derivative whose value is derived from the [credit risk](../Course%20Notes/Quantitative%20Trading%20Strategies%20Lecture%20Notes.md) on an underlying bond, loan or any other financial asset. In this way, the [credit risk](../Course%20Notes/Quantitative%20Trading%20Strategies%20Lecture%20Notes.md) is on an entity other than the. counterparties to the transaction itsel.] This entity is known as the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) and may be a corporate, a. sovereign or any other form of legal entity which has incurred debt.2] [Credit derivatives](../Credit%20Markets/RISK%20NEUTRAL%20VALUATION%20FRAMEWORK%20FOR%20CREDIT%20DEFAULT%20SWAPS.md) are bilateral contracts. between a buyer and seller under which the seller sells protection against the [credit risk](../Course%20Notes/Quantitative%20Trading%20Strategies%20Lecture%20Notes.md) of the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md).[2]  

Stated in plain language, a credit derivative is a wager, and the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) is the thing being wagered on. Similar to placing a bet at the racetrack, where the person placing the bet does not own the horse or the track or have. anything else to do with the race, the person buying the credit derivative doesn't necessarily own the bond (the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md)) that is the object of the wager. He or she simply believes that there is a good chance that the bond or collateralized debt obligation (CDO) in question will default (go to zero value). Originally conceived as a kind of. insurance policy for owners of bonds or CDO's, it evolved into a freestanding [investment](../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) strategy. The cost might be. as low as $1\%$ per year. If the buyer of the derivative believes the underlying bond will go bust within a year (usually. an extremely unlikely event) the buyer stands to reap a 100 fold profit. A small handful of investors anticipated the. credit crunch of 2007/8 and made billions placing "bets" via this method..  

The parties will select which credit events apply to a transaction and these usually consist of one or more of the following:  

bankruptcy (the risk that the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) will become bankrupt)   
.failure to pay (the risk that the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) will default on one of its obligations such as a bond or loan)   
obligation default (the risk that the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) will default on any of its obligations) obligation acceleration (the risk that an obligation of the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) will be accelerated e.g. a bond will be declared immediately due and payable following a default) repudiation/moratorium (the risk that the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) or a government will declare a moratorium over the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md)'s obligations) restructuring (the risk that obligations of the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) will be restructured)...  

Where credit protection is bought and sold between bilateral counterparties, this is known as an unfunded credit derivative. If the credit derivative is entered into by a financial institution or a [special purpose vehicle](../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20II%20CASH%20FLOW%20ENGINEERING/Chapter%2010%20-%20Collateralized%20Debt%20Obligations%20and%20Basket%20Credit%20Derivatives/Collateralized%20Debt%20Obligations.md) (SPV) and. payments under the credit derivative are funded using [securitization](10.%20Other%20Topics%20in%20Quantitative%20Finance.md) techniques, such that a debt obligation is issued. by the financial institution or SPV to support these obligations, this is known as a funded credit derivative..  

This synthetic [securitization process](../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Fixed%20Income%20Lecture%20Notes/Teaching%20Note%206%20Mortgage%20Backed%20Securities.md) has become increasingly popular over the last decade, with the simple versions of these structures being known as synthetic CDOs; credit linked notes; single tranche CDOs, to name a few. In funded [credit derivatives](../Credit%20Markets/RISK%20NEUTRAL%20VALUATION%20FRAMEWORK%20FOR%20CREDIT%20DEFAULT%20SWAPS.md), transactions are often rated by rating agencies, which allows investors to take different  

slices of [credit risk](../Course%20Notes/Quantitative%20Trading%20Strategies%20Lecture%20Notes.md) according to their risk appetite.  

# Market size and participants  

Credit default products are the most commonly traded credit derivative product'3] and include unfunded products such as credit default swaps and funded products such as [collateralized debt obligations](../Credit%20Markets/Credit%20Markets%20Session%205.md) (see further discussion below).  

The ISDA!4| reported in April 2007 that total notional amount on outstanding [credit derivatives](../Credit%20Markets/RISK%20NEUTRAL%20VALUATION%20FRAMEWORK%20FOR%20CREDIT%20DEFAULT%20SWAPS.md) was $\$35.1$ trillion with a gross market value of $\$948$ billion (ISDA's Website [5]). As reported in The Times on September 15, 2008, the "Worldwide [credit derivatives](../Credit%20Markets/RISK%20NEUTRAL%20VALUATION%20FRAMEWORK%20FOR%20CREDIT%20DEFAULT%20SWAPS.md) market i valued at \$62 trillion". [6]  

Although the [credit derivatives](../Credit%20Markets/RISK%20NEUTRAL%20VALUATION%20FRAMEWORK%20FOR%20CREDIT%20DEFAULT%20SWAPS.md) market is a global one, London has a market share of about $40\%$ , with the rest of Europe having about 10% [3]  

The main market participants are banks, [hedge funds](Basis%20Trade%20Explainer.md), insurance companies, pension funds, and other corporates.3]  

# Types  

[Credit derivatives](../Credit%20Markets/RISK%20NEUTRAL%20VALUATION%20FRAMEWORK%20FOR%20CREDIT%20DEFAULT%20SWAPS.md) are fundamentally divided into two categories: funded [credit derivatives](../Credit%20Markets/RISK%20NEUTRAL%20VALUATION%20FRAMEWORK%20FOR%20CREDIT%20DEFAULT%20SWAPS.md) and unfunded credit. [derivatives](../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Trading%20and%20Markets/Chapter%209%20Arbitrage%20and%20Hedging%20With%20Options.md). An unfunded credit derivative is a bilateral contract between two counterparties, where each party is responsible for making its payments under the contract (i.e. payments of premiums and any cash or [physical settlement](../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Fundamentals%20of%20Futures%20and%20Forwards.md) amount) itself without recourse to other assets. A funded credit derivative involves the [protection seller](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md). (the party that assumes the [credit risk](../Course%20Notes/Quantitative%20Trading%20Strategies%20Lecture%20Notes.md)) making an initial payment that is used to settle any potential credit events. However, the [protection buyer](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) is exposed to the [credit risk](../Course%20Notes/Quantitative%20Trading%20Strategies%20Lecture%20Notes.md) of the [protection seller](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md), in which case the [protection seller](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) fails to pay the [protection buyer](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) under the event of the [protection seller](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md)'s default. It is also known as counterparty. risk.  

Unfunded credit derivative products include the following products:  

[Credit default swap](../Credit%20Markets/Credit%20Market%20Session%202.md) (CDS)   
Total return swap   
Constant maturity [credit default swap](../Credit%20Markets/Credit%20Market%20Session%202.md) (CMCDS)   
First to Default [Credit Default Swap](../Credit%20Markets/Credit%20Market%20Session%202.md)   
[Portfolio](../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) [Credit Default Swap](../Credit%20Markets/Credit%20Market%20Session%202.md)   
Secured Loan [Credit Default Swap](../Credit%20Markets/Credit%20Market%20Session%202.md)   
[Credit Default Swap](../Credit%20Markets/Credit%20Market%20Session%202.md) on [Asset Backed Securities](Derivatives/Part%20X%20-%20Credit%20Derivatives/Chapter%2043%20-%20Securitisation,%20ABSs%20and%20CDOs.md)   
Credit default swaption   
Recovery lock transaction   
[Credit Spread](../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2014/Cds-Equivalent%20Bond%20Spread.md) Option   
CDS index products  

Funded credit derivative products include the following products:  

Credit linked note (CLN) Synthetic Collateralised Debt Obligation (CDO) Constant Proportion Debt Obligation (CPDO) Synthetic Constant Proportion [Portfolio](../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) Insurance (Synthetic CPPI)  

# Key unfunded credit derivative products  

# Credit default swap  

The [credit default swap](../Credit%20Markets/Credit%20Market%20Session%202.md) or CDS has become the cornerstone product of the [credit derivatives](../Credit%20Markets/RISK%20NEUTRAL%20VALUATION%20FRAMEWORK%20FOR%20CREDIT%20DEFAULT%20SWAPS.md) market. This product represents over thirty percent of the [credit derivatives](../Credit%20Markets/RISK%20NEUTRAL%20VALUATION%20FRAMEWORK%20FOR%20CREDIT%20DEFAULT%20SWAPS.md) market3]  

A [credit default swap](../Credit%20Markets/Credit%20Market%20Session%202.md), in its simplest form (the unfunded single name [credit default swap](../Credit%20Markets/Credit%20Market%20Session%202.md)) is a bilateral contract between a [protection buyer](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) and a [protection seller](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md). The [credit default swap](../Credit%20Markets/Credit%20Market%20Session%202.md) will reference the creditworthiness of a third party called a [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md): this will usually be a corporate or sovereign. The [credit default swap](../Credit%20Markets/Credit%20Market%20Session%202.md) will relate to the specified debt obligations of the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md): perhaps its bonds and loans, which fulfill certain pre-agreed characteristics. The [protection buyer](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) will pay a periodic fee to the [protection seller](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) in return for a contingent payment by the seller upon a [credit event](Valuation%20of%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) affecting the obligations of the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) specified in the transaction.  

The relevant credit events specified in a transaction will usually be selected from amongst the following:  

:The bankruptcy of the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md);   
:Its failure to pay in relation to a covered obligation;.   
:It defaulting on an obligation or that obligation being accelerated;   
: It agreeing to restructure a covered obligation or a repudiation or moratorium being declared over any covered obligation.  

If any of these events occur and the [protection buyer](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) serves a [credit event](Valuation%20of%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) notice on the [protection seller](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) detailing the [credit event](Valuation%20of%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) as well as (usually) providing some publicly available information validating this claim, then the transaction will settle.  

This means that, in the case of a physically settled transaction, the [protection buyer](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) can deliver an amount of the.   
[reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md)'s defaulted obligations to the [protection seller](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md), in return for their full face value (notwithstanding that.   
they are now worth far less). In the case of a cash settled transaction, a relevant obligation of the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) will be valued and the [protection seller](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) will pay the [protection buyer](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) the full face value of the reference obligation less its.   
current value (i.e. compensating the [protection buyer](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) for the decline in the obligation's creditworthiness)..  

Credit default swaps have unique characteristics that distinguish them from insurance products and financial guaranties. The [protection buyer](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) does not need to own an underlying obligation of the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md). The [protection buyer](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) does not need to suffer a loss.  

Since the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) is not a party to agreement between the [protection buyer](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) and seller, the seller of protection. has no inherent recourse to the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) in the event of default and no right to sue the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) for recovery. However, if the transaction were to be physically settled the seller of protection could derive a right to take. action against the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) on the basis of the loan or securities acquired during the settlement process..  

The product has many variations, including where there is a basket or [portfolio](../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) of reference entities, although fundamentally, the principles remain the same. A powerful recent variation has been gathering market share of late: credit default swaps which relate to [asset-backed](../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%207-%20CP,%20Repo,%20and%20the%20Crisis/Asset%20Backed%20Commercial%20Paper%20Understanding%20the%20Risks.md) securities[7l  

# Total return swap  

A total return swap (also known as Total Rate of Return Swap) is a contract between two counterparties whereby they swap periodic payments for the period of the contract. Typically, one party receives the total return (interest payments plus any capital gains or losses for the payment period) from a specified reference asset, while the other receives a specified fixed or floating [cash flow](../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%201%20-%20Purpose%20and%20Structure%20of%20Financial%20Markets/Preview%20of%20the%20Book.md) that is not related to the creditworthiness of the reference asset, as with a vanilla [Interest rate swap](Primer%20on%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md). The payments are based upon the same notional amount. The reference asset may be any asset, index or basket of assets.  

The TRS is simply a mechanism that allows one party to derive the economic benefit of owning an asset without use of the balance sheet, and which allows the other to effectively "buy protection" against loss in value due to ownership of a credit asset.  

The essential difference between a total return swap and a [credit default swap](../Credit%20Markets/Credit%20Market%20Session%202.md) is that the [credit default swap](../Credit%20Markets/Credit%20Market%20Session%202.md) provides protection against specific credit events. The total return swap protects against the loss of value irrespective of cause, whether default, widening of credit spreads or anything else i.e. it isolates both [credit risk](../Course%20Notes/Quantitative%20Trading%20Strategies%20Lecture%20Notes.md) and [market risk](Derivatives/Part%20I%20-%20Forwards%20and%20Futures/Chapter%205%20-%20Index%20Futures.md).  

