# Credit default swap  

A [credit default swap](../Credit%20Markets/Credit%20Market%20Session%202.md) (CDS) is a swap. contract and agreement in which the [protection buyer](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) of the CDS makes a series of payments (often referred to as the CDS "fee" or "spread") to the [protection seller](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md). and, in exchange, receives a payoff if a credit instrument (typically a bond or loan) experiences a [credit event](Valuation%20of%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md). It is a form of reverse trading.  

In its simplest form, a [credit default swap](../Credit%20Markets/Credit%20Market%20Session%202.md) is a bilateral contract between the buyer and seller of protection. The CDS will refer to a "[reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md)" or "reference obligor", usually a corporation or government. The [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) is not a party to the contract. The [protection buyer](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) makes quarterly premium paymentsthe "spread"to the [protection seller](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md). If the [reference entity](../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes%209A-%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md). defaults, the [protection seller](../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md) pays the buyer the par value of the bond in exchange for physical delivery of the bond, although settlement may also be by cash or auction.11]. [2] A default is referred to as a "[credit event](Valuation%20of%20Credit%20Default%20Swaps.md)" and includes such events as failure to pay, restructuring and bankruptcy.[2] Most CDSs are in the. $\$10â€“$ million range with maturities between one and 10 years.3]  

A holder of a bond may "buy protection" to hedge its risk of default. In this way, a CDS is similar to credit insurance, although CDS are not similar to or subject to regulations governing casualty or life insurance. Also, investors can buy and sell protection without  

